# Question 3
| $m$ | $y \pm 0.01$(m) | $\theta$(rad) | $sin(\theta)$ (au) | $m\lambda$ (m) |
| --- | --------------- | ------------- | ------------------ | -------------- |
| 1   | 6.28E-03        | 5.54E-03      | 5.54E-03           | 5.32E-07       |
| 2   | 1.34E-02        | 1.18E-02      | 1.18E-02           | 1.06E-06       |
| 3   | 1.96E-02        | 1.73E-02      | 1.73E-02           | 1.60E-06       |
| 4   | 2.65E-02        | 2.33E-02      | 2.33E-02           | 2.13E-06       |
| 5   | 3.36E-02        | 2.96E-02      | 2.96E-02           | 2.66E-06       |
| 6   | 4.08E-02        | 3.59E-02      | 3.59E-02           | 3.19E-06       |
Table 1: Table of measurements. The equation that governs this relationship is $m\lambda = d\sin(\theta)$. $y$ is the distance from the center maxima to the minima at the current $m$. $\theta$ is calculated given that we know x is the distance from the screen and $\theta = ATAN(y/x)$. $\lambda$ of the laser is known.
> ![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 3: Distance as angle changes The equation that governs this relationship is $m\lambda = d\sin(\theta)$ which is a linear relationship in $m\lambda$ and $\sin(\theta)$. We are able to find the width of the hair $d$ by finding the slope of this graph. Equation of linear fit is 
$m\lambda = (88.1 \pm 0.9 \space (\mu m))\sin(\theta) + (0.05 \pm 0.02 (\mu m))$
Meaning that my hair is $88.1 \pm 0.9 \space \mu m$ thick

No since our analysis relies on the fact that wavelength is constant, polychromatic light which contains many different wavelengths would not work, also there would not necessarily be a clear diffraction pattern for incandescent light so that might also be a slight problem
# Question 5

The minima and maxima would be closer together as in the equation $m\lambda = d\sin(\theta)$ if everything else is constant and only wavelength goes down, that must mean $\sin(\theta)$ would go down meaning that $\theta$ goes down meaning closer together spots
